Related C++ code:
  - C++ has NO equivalent display list / draw list concept. The C++ architecture uses a fundamentally different parallelization strategy:
    - src/emCore/emViewRenderer.cpp:132-146 — C++ uses emThreadMiniMutex (UserSpaceMutex) to serialize access to shared panel data during concurrent rendering
    - include/emCore/emViewRenderer.h:100-105 — ThreadPool, UserSpaceMutex fields
    - include/emCore/emRenderThreadPool.h — C++ thread pool that renders tiles directly, with mutex-protected access to panel tree
  - In C++, each render thread calls Paint() methods directly on panels while holding/releasing a UserSpaceMutex. In Rust, Rc<Look> in panel behaviors prevents Send/Sync across threads.
  - Structural differences: The Rust DrawList is an architectural divergence required by Rust's ownership model. C++ can share mutable state via mutex; Rust cannot send Rc across threads. The solution: Phase 1 (single-threaded) records all draw calls into a DrawList, Phase 2 (parallel) replays the DrawList into tile buffers. This replaces C++'s mutex-based concurrent panel tree traversal with a record-then-replay pattern. The DrawOp enum serializes the full painter API surface.

OPEN QUESTIONS:
  - The unsafe Send/Sync impls for DrawOp rely on the invariant that emImage pointers remain valid between recording and replay. This is documented in comments but not enforced by the type system.

