REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

Rust file: src/emCore/emPainterDrawList.rs

Architectural divergence from C++ — no C++ equivalent exists.

C++ rendering: each worker thread calls Paint() on panels directly,
  synchronized via userSpaceMutex (emThreadMiniMutex). Threads share
  mutable access to the panel tree.

Rust rendering: single-threaded recording phase captures all paint
  calls as DrawOp enum variants into a DrawList. Parallel replay phase
  executes DrawOps into tile buffers. User paint code never runs on
  worker threads.

Why: panel state uses Rc (e.g. emLook.rs:22 returns Rc<Self>).
  Rc is not Send — cannot share across threads.
  The record-replay pattern decouples user code from threading.

DrawOp has 37 variants covering the full emPainter API surface.
6 variants contain *const emImage raw pointers:
  PaintImageFull, PaintImageColored, PaintImageScaled,
  PaintBorderImage, PaintImageSimple, PaintBorderImageColored

unsafe impl Send/Sync for DrawOp relies on three invariants:
  1. Images are owned by panel behaviors in the PanelTree
  2. The PanelTree is not modified between recording and replay
  3. std::thread::scope ensures all replay threads complete before returning

These are runtime invariants not enforced by the type system.

Verified: invariant #2 is upheld by the frame loop structure.
  emWindow::render_parallel() (emWindow.rs:374-458) proceeds in three
  sequential phases:
    Phase 1 (lines 390-406): Records draw ops into DrawList.
      tree is passed as &mut PanelTree to view.Paint() (emView.rs:2201).
      Paint calls paint_panel_recursive (emView.rs:2386), which mutates
      tree via take_behavior/put_behavior (emPanelTree.rs:999-1008) to
      borrow behaviors for painting. Each behavior is restored before
      its subtree recursion completes. The same pattern applies to
      self.control_tree (lines 398-404). All behaviors (and their owned
      images) are back in both trees when Phase 1 ends at line 406.
    Phase 2 (lines 422-445): Replays DrawList into tile buffers in
      parallel via render_pool.CallParallel(). This closure captures
      only draw_list_ref (&DrawList) and results_ref — it does NOT
      reference tree at all. No code path between Phase 1 end (line 406)
      and Phase 2 start (line 432) touches the tree; lines 408-420 only
      read self.tile_cache.
    Phase 3 (lines 447-458): Uploads tiles to GPU. Single-threaded,
      after CallParallel returns (std::thread::scope guarantees all
      worker threads have joined).
Verified: same phase structure exists in emViewRenderer.rs:
  emViewRenderer::render_parallel() (emViewRenderer.rs:37-97) follows
  identical phase separation:
    Phase 1 (lines 47-52): Records into DrawList via recording emPainter.
    Phase 2 (lines 54-81): pool.CallParallel() closure captures only
      draw_list_ref (&DrawList) and results_ref — no tree reference.
    Phase 3 (lines 83-97): Composites tiles into framebuffer.
  The same structural guarantee applies: Phase 2's closure does not
  capture tree.

  The guarantee is structural, not type-level: Phase 2's closure simply
  does not capture or access the PanelTree. The &mut PanelTree borrow
  on render_parallel's signature does not enforce this — Rust would
  allow tree access between Phases 1 and 2 since the recording borrow
  has ended. A future refactor could accidentally introduce tree access
  in Phase 2, breaking the invariant without a compile error.
  Risk: LOW. The separation is clear in the code structure, and the
  closure's capture list would make accidental tree access a visible
  change. However, this remains a runtime invariant, not a type-level
  guarantee.

RefCell / interior mutability risk: NONE.
  DrawOp variants contain only plain owned data: f64, u32, u8, bool,
  emColor (packed u32), String, Vec<(f64, f64)>, emStroke, emTexture,
  and *const emImage raw pointers. None of these types contain RefCell
  or Rc — verified by grep (no RefCell/Rc in emPainterDrawList.rs,
  emStroke.rs, or emTexture.rs). DrawList itself is struct { ops:
  Vec<DrawOp> } with no interior mutability.
  The *const emImage pointers point directly at emImage values owned
  by panel behaviors. While behaviors are accessed through RefCell in
  the PanelTree, the raw pointer bypasses the RefCell — it addresses
  the emImage inside the behavior struct, not the RefCell wrapper.
  During Phase 2 replay, no code path touches the PanelTree or any
  RefCell; the closure captures only &DrawList (immutable, no RefCell)
  and output buffers (each tile's Mutex<Option<emImage>> is thread-
  local by index). There is no path through which a replay thread
  could reach a RefCell.
